9,-0.01584843,0.03322661,0.03522060,0.03736590,0.06180343,0.08891832,0.01238045,0.04446803,-0.01632308,0.06801940,-0.04386430,0.01349679,0.06583538,-0.00304575,-0.02646856,-0.04906175,-0.07147224,-0.04934588,-0.01080147,0.00020595,-0.02592188,0.08416130,-0.06434538,-0.04547236,-0.08235650,-0.02967043,0.01592950,-0.01851943,0.03241660,0.00412019,-0.01993549,0.02031673,-0.03612703,-0.01219502,0.01655125,-0.03570497,0.05748446,0.03664018,-0.04614988,0.07653236,0.01457957,0.01766961]',E'Creating a New Branch\n\n(((branches, creating)))\nWhat happens when you create a new branch?\nWell, doing so creates a new pointer for you to move around.\nLet''s say you want to create a new branch called `testing`.\nYou do this with the `git branch` command:(((git commands, branch)))\n\n[source,console]\n----\n$ git branch testing\n----\n\nThis creates a new pointer to the same commit you''re currently on.','{"source": "git", "version": "2", "language": "bash", "title": "Nutshell.Asc", "section_title": "nutshell.asc", "url": "https://github.com/progit/progit2/blob/main/book/03-git-branching/sections/nutshell.asc", "topics": "git,vcs,branching,nutshell.asc", "categories": "devops,vcs,scm"}');
