5448661,0.03154955,0.03442874,-0.01017410,-0.02453102,0.03345867,0.07378999,0.04912133,0.03058523,-0.02115676,0.08334022,-0.05154492,0.00771314,0.03240647,0.01310172,-0.03188537,-0.00699740,-0.06547729,-0.04146245,0.01142418,-0.04828447,-0.02394391,0.11131373,-0.09099463,-0.01099797,-0.03672866,-0.00452781,-0.04039503,-0.01173236,0.03215859,-0.02811585,-0.04211723,0.06326623,0.00586934,-0.04004882,-0.03549004,-0.06190533,0.07416984,0.02004506,-0.04723989,0.08404287,0.00072932,0.01132881]',E'Creating a New Branch\n\nHow does Git know what branch you''re currently on?\nIt keeps a special pointer called `HEAD`.\nNote that this is a lot different than the concept of `HEAD` in other VCSs you may be used to, such as Subversion or CVS.\nIn Git, this is a pointer to the local branch you''re currently on.\nIn this case, you''re still on `master`.\nThe `git branch` command only _created_ a new branch -- it didn''t switch to that branch.\n\n.HEAD pointing to a branch\nimage::images/head-to-master.png[HEAD pointing to a branch]','{"source": "git", "version": "2", "language": "bash", "title": "Nutshell.Asc", "section_title": "nutshell.asc", "url": "https://github.com/progit/progit2/blob/main/book/03-git-branching/sections/nutshell.asc", "topics": "git,vcs,branching,nutshell.asc", "categories": "devops,vcs,scm"}');
